You are right, the if statement is not actually checking if the date object is more than one day older than `new Date()`. The problem is that the `new Date()` function returns the current date and time, but the `sortDate` variable is only set to the date value, not the time value. So, if the `sortDate` variable is set to a date that is one day before the current date, the if statement will still return true.

To fix this, we need to convert the `sortDate` variable to a UTC date object. UTC is a time zone that is used to coordinate international time. To convert a date object to UTC, we can use the `Date.UTC()` function. The `Date.UTC()` function takes two arguments: the year, and the number of milliseconds since January 1, 1970, UTC.

Here is the modified code:

```javascript
// Loop through the child elements of the tbody element with id "target_table"
var items = document.getElementById("target_table").children;

// For each item element, get the value of the "data-sort" attribute in the 8th child
for (var i = 0; i < items.length; i++) {
  var item = items[i];
  var sortValue = item.children[7].getAttribute("data-sort");

  // Convert the sort value to a number and multiply it by 1000
  var sortDate = new Date(Number(sortValue) * 1000);

  // Convert the sortDate variable to a UTC date object
  var utcSortDate = new Date(sortDate.getTime() - (sortDate.getTimezoneOffset() * 60000));

  // If the date of the new date object is more than 1 day older than the current date
  if (utcSortDate > new Date()) {
    // Change the display style of the original item element to "none"
    item.style.display = "none";
